    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-01-14T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-01-14T04:00:00-05:00" n="51"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d51">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01/1–1449: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-01-14T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 14, 1949—5 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:59 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>127. Executive local airline saw Vice Minister Foreign Affairs<note n="86"
                        xml:id="d51fn86">Tung Lin, Chinese Administrative Vice Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> January 13 and in course his endeavors sell Vice Minister
                    use of civil airlines for evacuation Government personnel, Nanking, was advised
                    that large scale air movement of Government personnel to Taiwan from Assistant
                    Minister level down was scheduled to be undertaken by CAF<note n="87"
                        xml:id="d51fn87">Chinese Air Force.</note> on January 15.</p>
                <p>Source also learned that CAF had moved from Nanking all motor vehicles which Air
                    Force elected to keep; last LST left Nanking with this equipment on January 13.
                    Source also quoted Vice Minister as saying he did not think that “cannon shots
                    would be heard in Nanking for about 3 weeks”.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 127; repeated Nanking 99.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
